{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nigeria", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Nigerian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Nigeria}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nigeria\n| map1 =  [[File:States &amp; Territory by confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Nigeria.jpg|States &amp; Territory by confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Nigeria|320px]]\n| legend1 = \n| map2 = <!-- File:COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Nigeria.svg -->\n| legend2 = <!-- {{center|Map of provinces with {{color|#c80000|confirmed}} or {{color|#558eed|suspected}} coronavirus cases}} -->\n| map3 = \n| legend3 = \n| disease = [[coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Nigeria]]\n| first_case = [[Lagos]]\n| arrival_date    = February 27, 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=02|day1=27|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}} ago)\n| origin = [[Milan]], [[Italy]]\n| deaths = 4\n| recovery_cases = 25\n| confirmed_cases =214\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili = \n| website = http://covid19.ncdc.gov.ng/\n}}\nThe first confirmed case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] in [[Nigeria]] was announced on 27 February 2020, when an Italian citizen in [[Lagos]] tested positive for the virus, caused by [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ncdc.gov.ng/news/227/first-case-of-corona-virus-disease-confirmed-in-nigeria|title=FIRST CASE OF CORONA VIRUS DISEASE CONFIRMED IN NIGERIA|date=28 February 2020|publisher=[[Nigeria Centre for Disease Control]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/28/world/africa/nigeria-coronavirus.html|title=Nigeria Responds to First Coronavirus Case in Sub-Saharan Africa|date=28 February 2020|last1=Maclean|first1=Ruth|last2=Dahir|first2=Abdi Latif|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref> On 9 March 2020, a second case of the virus was reported in [[Ewekoro]], [[Ogun State]], a Nigerian citizen who had contact with the Italian citizen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pmnewsnigeria.com/2020/03/09/breaking-nigeria-records-second-case-of-coronavirus|title=Nigeria records second case of Coronavirus|date=9 March 2020|website=[[P.M. News]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nOn 28 January 2020, the [[Federal government of Nigeria]] assured citizens of the country of its readiness to strengthen surveillance at [[List of airports in Nigeria|five international airports]] in the country to prevent the spread of coronavirus. The government announced the airports as [[Enugu State|Enugu]], [[Lagos State|Lagos]], [[Rivers State|Rivers]], [[Kano State|Kano]] and the [[Federal Capital Territory, Nigeria|FCT]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/top-news/374865-coronavirus-nigeria-strengthens-surveillance-at-five-international-airports.html|title=Coronavirus: Nigeria 'strengthens' surveillance at five international airports|publisher=[[Premium Times]]|date=29 January 2020|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Nigeria Centre for Disease Control]] also announced same day that they had already set up coronavirus group and was ready to activate its incident system if any case emerged in Nigeria.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://dailypost.ng/2020/01/28/coronavirus-nigeria-announces-preventive-measures-releases-numbers|title=Coronavirus: Nigeria announces preventive measures, releases numbers|publisher=[[Daily Post (Nigeria)|Daily Post Nigeria]]|last=Odunsi|first=Wale|date=28 January 2020|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January 2020, following the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|developments of COVID-19 pandemic in mainland China]] and other countries worldwide, the federal government of Nigeria set up a Coronavirus Preparedness Group to mitigate the impact of the virus if it eventually spreads to the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thisdaylive.com/index.php/2020/01/31/fg-sets-up-coronavirus-preparedness-group|title=FG Sets up Coronavirus Preparedness Group|last=Ifijeh|first=Martins|publisher=[[This Day|This Day Newspaper]]|date=31 January 2020|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.msn.com/en-xl/africa/nigeria/steps-nigeria-is-taking-to-prepare-for-coronavirus/ar-BBZqjKe|title=Steps Nigeria is taking to prepare for coronavirus|date=29 January 2020|access-date=10 March 2020|website=[[MSN]]}}</ref> On the same day, the [[World Health Organization]] listed Nigeria among other 13 African countries identified as high-risk for the spread of the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thisdaylive.com/index.php/2020/02/01/coronavirus-spread-who-lists-nigeria-among-high-risk-countries|title=Coronavirus Spread: WHO Lists Nigeria Among High Risk Countries|last1=Ezigbo|first1=Onyebuchi|last2=Ifijeh|first2=Martins|publisher=[[This Day|This Day Newspaper]]|date=1 February 2020|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 February 2020, a [[Chinese people|Chinese]] citizen presented himself to the [[Government of Lagos State|Lagos State government]] on suspicion of being infected with coronavirus. He was admitted at [[Reddington Hospital]] and was released the following day after testing negative.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://tribuneonlineng.com/breaking-coronavirus-scare-in-lagos-govt-announces-test-result-on-chinese-citizen|title=BREAKING: Coronavirus scare in Lagos, govt announces test result on Chinese citizen|publisher=[[Nigerian Tribune]]|last=Gesinde|first=Seyi|date=27 February 2020|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> There's widespread belief among Nigerians on the roots of the pandemic. Some have agreed to the mainstream reason for its origin which is zoonotic in nature as agreed upon by world's reputable scientists who gave a conclusive report after intense research on the virus while others believe in an ongoing conspiracy theory that the virus was a lab creation at the region where it broke out. Others have attributed it as a punishment from God due to the sins of mankind.\n\n==Timeline==\n{{align|right|{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Nigeria medical cases chart}}}}\n\n===February===\nOn 27 February, Nigeria confirmed its first case in Lagos State, an Italian citizen who works in Nigeria had returned on 25 February from Milan, Italy through the [[Murtala Muhammed International Airport]], fell ill on 26 February and was transferred to Lagos State Biosecurity Facilities for isolation and testing.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ncdc.gov.ng/news/227/first-case-of-corona-virus-disease-confirmed-in-nigeria |title=Nigeria Centre for Disease Control |website=ncdc.gov.ng |access-date=8 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302150128/https://ncdc.gov.ng/news/227/first-case-of-corona-virus-disease-confirmed-in-nigeria |archive-date=2 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-51671834 |title=Nigeria confirms first coronavirus case |date=28 February 2020 |website=BBC News |language=en-GB |access-date=8 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302181240/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-51671834 |archive-date=2 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"ConfirmedNigeria\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pmnewsnigeria.com/2020/02/28/breaking-deadly-coronavirus-confirmed-in-lagos-nigeria-at-last/|title=Breaking: Deadly Coronavirus confirmed in Lagos, Nigeria at last|date=25 February 2020|access-date=28 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228011403/https://www.pmnewsnigeria.com/2020/02/28/breaking-deadly-coronavirus-confirmed-in-lagos-nigeria-at-last/|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pmnewsnigeria.com/2020/02/28/breaking-deadly-coronavirus-confirmed-in-lagos-nigeria-at-last|title=Breaking: Deadly Coronavirus confirmed in Lagos Nigeria at last|last=Ugbodaga|first=Kazeem|date=28 February 2020|website=[[P.M. News]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/africa/nigeria-confirms-first-case-of-coronavirus/1748081|title=Nigeria confirms first case of coronavirus|last=Tih|first=Felix|date=28 February 2020|website=[[Anadolu Agency]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March===\nOn 9 March, the second case was confirmed, a Nigerian citizen in [[Ewekoro]], [[Ogun State]] who had contact with the Italian citizen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelstv.com/2020/03/09/breaking-nigeria-confirms-second-case-of-coronavirus|title=Nigeria Confirms Second Case Of Coronavirus|publisher=[[Channels TV]]|date=9 March 2020|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/health/health-news/380886-updated-coronavirus-second-case-confirmed-in-nigeria.html|last=Owoseye|first=Ayodamola|title=UPDATED: Coronavirus: Second case confirmed in Nigeria|publisher=[[Premium Times]]|date=9 March 2020|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/dont-panic-says-govt-as-nigeria-gets-second-coronavirus-case|title=Don't panic, says govt as Nigeria gets second coronavirus case|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=10 March 2020|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, Nigeria confirmed that the second case no longer had the virus in his system and thus tested negative.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigerian-who-tested-postive-for-coronavirus-now-negative|title=UPDATED: Nigerian who tested positive for coronavirus now negative|last=Atoyebi|first=Olufemi|date=13 March 2020|accessdate=13 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, Nigeria confirmed the third case in Lagos State, A 30-year-old Nigerian female citizen that returned on 13 March from the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecable.ng/breaking-third-coronavirus-case-confirmed-in-lagos|title=Third coronavirus case confirmed in Nigeria|last=Olatunji|first=Haleem|date=17 March 2020|publisher=[[TheCable]]|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, Nigeria confirmed five new cases of the virus: four of the new cases were discovered in Lagos State, while one was discovered in [[Ekiti State]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/news/local/coronavirus-nigeria-confirms-5-new-cases/bfderkf|title=Coronavirus: Nigeria confirms 5 new cases|last=Toromade|first=Samson|date=18 March 2020|publisher=Pulse NG|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, Nigeria confirmed four new cases of the virus in Lagos State.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/breaking-lagos-confirms-four-new-cases-of-covid-19|title=BREAKING: Lagos confirms four new cases of COVID-19|last=Royal|first=David|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]|date=19 March 2020|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://guardian.ng/news/nigerias-coronavirus-cases-rises-to-12-with-four-new-confirmations|last=Erezi|first=Dennis|title=Nigeria's coronavirus cases rises to 12 with four new confirmations|date=19 March 2020|publisher=[[The Guardian (Nigeria)|The Guardian Newspaper]]|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> Nigerian government also announced that the Italian citizen who brought coronavirus to Nigeria has tested negative and was discharged the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-italian-who-brought-coronavirus-to-nigeria-now-negative-lagos|title=Italian who brought coronavirus to Nigeria now negative \u2013 Lagos|last=Ojerinde|first=Dayo|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=20 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-italian-who-brought-coronavirus-to-nigeria-discharged|title=UPDATED: Italian who brought coronavirus to Nigeria discharged|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, Nigeria confirmed ten new cases: seven in Lagos State, three in the [[Federal Capital Territory, Nigeria|FCT]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/updated-nigeria-records-10-new-positive-cases-of-covid-19|title=UPDATED: Nigeria records 10 new positive cases of COVID-19|last=Emorinken|first=Moses|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=21 March 2020|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, Nigeria confirmed eight new cases: six in Lagos State, one in [[Oyo State]], and one in the FCT.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/coronavirus-nigeria-now-has-26-confirmed-cases-ncdc|title=Coronavirus: Nigeria now has 26 Confirmed cases \u2013 NCDC|last=Alao|first=Abiodun|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=22 March 2020|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/breaking-covid-19-ncdc-confirms-one-new-case-in-fct|title=BREAKING: COVID-19: NCDC confirms one new case in FCT|last=Emorinken|first=Moses|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=22 March 2020|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/coronavirus-ncdc-confirms-30-cases-in-nigeria|title=[BREAKING] Coronavirus: NCDC confirms 30 cases in Nigeria|last=Atoyebi|first=Olufemi|date=22 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, Nigeria confirmed ten new cases: six in Lagos State, three in the FCT and one in [[Edo State]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://guardian.ng/breakingnews/nigerias-coronavirus-toll-cases-now-40|last=Onyedika-Ugoeze|first=Nkechi|title=Nigeria's coronavirus cases now 40|date=23 March 2020|publisher=[[The Guardian (Nigeria)|The Guardian Newspaper]]|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> They also confirmed their first death, a 67-year-old Suleiman Achimugu, an engineer and former managing director of Pipelines and products Marketing Company, who returned from United Kingdom with underlying health conditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pmnewsnigeria.com/2020/03/23/achimugu-ex-ppmc-boss-identified-as-nigerias-first-coronavirus-death|title=Achimugu, ex-PPMC boss identified as Nigeria\u2019s first coronavirus death|date=23 March 2020|website=[[P.M. News]]|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/covid-19-updated-first-death-recorded-as-confirmed-cases-rise-to-36|title=COVID-19: UPDATED: First death recorded as confirmed cases rise to 36|last=Emorinken|first=Moses|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=23 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, Nigeria confirmed four new cases: one in Lagos State, one in Ogun State, one in [[Bauchi State]], and one in the FCT.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-44|title=Nigeria coronavirus cases rise to 44|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, Nigeria confirmed seven new cases: three in Lagos State, one in [[Osun State]], one in Rivers State, and two in the FCT.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/updated-coronavirus-cases-hit-51-in-nigeria|title=UPDATED: Coronavirus cases hit 51 in Nigeria|last=Ojerinde|first=Dayo|date=25 March 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, Nigeria confirmed fourteen new cases: twelve in Lagos State, one in Bauchi State and one in the FCT.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channelstv.com/2020/03/26/breaking-14-new-cases-of-covid-19-confirmed|title=14 New Cases Of COVID-19 Confirmed In Nigeria|publisher=[[Channels TV]]|date=26 March 2020|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref> Nigeria announced that they were tracing 4,370 suspected cases of the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/coronavirus-nigeria-tracing-4370-suspected-cases-\u2015-lai-mohammed|title=CORONAVIRUS: Nigeria tracing 4370 suspected cases \u2015 Lai Mohammed|last=Soni|first=Daniel|date=26 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March, Nigeria confirmed sixteen new cases: eight in Lagos State, three in the FCT, two in [[Enugu State]], two in Oyo State, and one in Edo State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-coronavirus-cases-rise-from-65-to-70-in-24-hours|title=BREAKING: Nigeria's COVID-19 cases rise from 65 to 70|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-coronavirus-cases-hit-81-as-ncdc-announces-11-new-cases|title=BREAKING: Nigeria's coronavirus cases hit 81 as NCDC announces 11 new cases|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=28 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> On the same day, Lagos State governor, [[Babajide Sanwo-Olu]] announced that the local governments with the highest number of cases are [[Eti-Osa]] and [[Ikeja]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-ikeja-eti-osa-top-coronavirus-cases-in-lagos|title=Ikeja, Eti-Osa top coronavirus cases in Lagos|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=27 March 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, Nigeria confirmed sixteen new cases: seven in Lagos State, four in Oyo State, two in the FCT, one in Osun State, one in [[Kaduna State]], and one in [[Benue State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-records-eight-new-covid-19-cases-total-now-89|title=UPDATED: Nigeria records eight new COVID-19 cases, total now 89|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=28 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-covid-19-nigerias-cases-hit-97|title=[BREAKING] COVID-19: Nigeria\u2019s cases hit 97|last=Oyero|first=Kayode|date=28 March 2020|accessdate=28 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, Nigeria confirmed sixteen new cases: nine in Lagos State, and five in the FCT.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-reports-14-new-cases-total-at-111|title=BREAKING: Nigeria reports 14 new cases, total at 111|last=Ojerinde|first=Dayo|date=29 March 2020|accessdate=29 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, Nigeria confirmed twenty new cases: thirteen in Lagos State, four in the FCT, two in Kaduna State and one in Oyo State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigerias-coronavirus-cases-now-131-as-ncdc-announces-20-new-infections|title=BREAKING: COVID-19 cases rise to 131 in Nigeria|last=Ojerinde|first=Dayo|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> Five persons were discharged with one death.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/covid-19-sanwo-olu-confirms-discharge-of-five-patients|title=COVID-19: Sanwo-Olu confirms discharge of five patients|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=30 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-records-second-coronavirus-death|title=UPDATED: Nigeria records second coronavirus death|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=30 March 2020|accessdate=30 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> The suspected cases that Nigeria were tracing, rose to 6,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/covid-19-ncdc-to-follow-up-over-6000-contacts-to-curb-spread-of-virus|title=COVID-19: NCDC to follow up over 6000 contacts to curb spread of virus|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=30 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April===\nOn 1 April, Nigeria confirmed thirty five new cases: nine in Osun State, nine in Lagos State, seven in the FCT, five in [[Akwa Ibom State]], two in Edo State, one in Ekiti State, one in Kaduna State, and one in Bauchi State.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-records-12-new-covid-19-cases-total-now-151|title=BREAKING: Nigeria records 12 new COVID-19 cases, total now 151|last=Oyero|first=Kayode|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-records-23-new-cases-total-now-174|title=BREAKING: Nigeria records 23 new cases of COVID-19, total now 174|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=1 April 2020|accessdate=1 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, Nigeria confirmed ten new cases: seven in Lagos State, and three in the FCT.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nigeria-records-10-new-cases-in-lagos-abuja|title=BREAKING: Nigeria records 10 new coronavirus cases in Lagos, Abuja|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> They also announced that eleven persons have been discharged.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-coronavirus-11-new-patients-recover-discharged-in-lagos|title=Coronavirus: 11 patients recover, discharged in Lagos|last=Ojerinde|first=Dayo|date=2 April 2020|accessdate=2 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, Nigeria confirmed twenty five new cases: eleven in Lagos State, six in Osun State, three in the FCT, three in Edo State, one in [[Ondo State]], and one in Oyo State.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/breaking-nigeria-records-six-new-cases-of-covid-19|title=BREAKING: Nigeria records six new cases of COVID-19|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=3 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref> They also announced that five persons have been discharged with two deaths.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/ncdc-apologises-for-error-in-covid-19-results-says-total-now-209|title=NCDC apologises for error in COVID-19 results, says total now 209|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=4 April 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> Nigeria announced that they have identified about 6,700 contacts and followed up on about 71 percent, testing about 4,000 people and possessing a total of eight testing labs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/covid-19-nigeria-gets-additional-labs-tests-4000|title=COVID-19: Nigeria gets additional labs, tests 4,000|last=Emorinken|first=Moses|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=3 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April, Nigeria confirmed five new cases: three in Bauchi State, and two in the FCT.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/breaking-nigeria-records-five-new-covid-19-cases-214-in-total|title=BREAKING: Nigeria records five new COVID-19 cases, 214 in total|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=4 April 2020|access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Nigeria medical cases}}\n\n==Reactions==\n===March===\nEarly March, the [[Federal Ministry of Health (Nigeria)|minister of health]] in Nigeria, [[Osagie Ehanire]], announced that 60 persons who had contact with the index Italian patient were under isolation, 40 persons in Ogun State and 20 in Lagos State.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thisdaylive.com/index.php/2020/03/08/coronavirus-outbreak-round-the-clock-updates|title=Coronavirus Outbreak: Round-the-clock Updates|last=Ifijeh|first=Martins|publisher=[[This Day|This Day Newspaper]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 March, four Chinese citizens were quarantined in [[Plateau State]], they all tested negative the following day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvcnews.tv/coronavirus-three-chinese-quarantined-in-plateau|title=Coronavirus: Three Chinese quarantined in Plateau|date=1 March 2020|publisher=[[TVC News]]|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/news/local/coronavirus-chinese-men-test-negative/qzk5jrp|title=Chinese men quarantined in Plateau over coronavirus test negative|last=Famuyiwa|first=Damilare|date=2 March 2020|publisher=Pulse NG|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 March, the governor of Lagos State, [[Babajide Sanwo-Olu]] disclosed that two foreign Nationals from an unnamed Asian country has tested negative to the virus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/regional/ssouth-west/379976-coronavirus-two-foreigners-in-nigeria-test-negative.html|title=Coronavirus: Two foreigners in Nigeria test negative|publisher=[[Premium Times]]|last=Adediran|first=Ifeoluwa|date=3 March 2020|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March, the [[Anambra State]] government announced that five Chinese citizens tested negative for the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/news/local/coronavirus-anambra-govt-says-5-chinese-citizens-test-negative/wem48xp|title=Coronavirus: Anambra govt says 5 Chinese citizens test negative|date=6 March 2020|publisher=Pulse NG|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref> The Nigeria Centre for Disease Control reported that a total of 219 primary and secondary contacts of the index case had been identified and were being actively monitored.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ncdc.gov.ng/themes/common/files/sitreps/02ca174a32597a1e20536b86bed723c7.pdf |title=NCDC Situation Report 6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March, the [[President of Nigeria|President]] [[Muhammadu Buhari]] established a Presidential Task Force for the control of the virus in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://guardian.ng/news/buhari-names-task-force-on-coronavirus|last=Daka|first=FTerhemba|title=Buhari names task force on coronavirus|date=10 March 2020|publisher=[[The Guardian (Nigeria)|The Guardian Newspaper]]|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/buhari-sets-up-12-member-task-force-to-control-coronavirus|title=Buhari sets up 12 member Task Force to control Coronavirus|last=Agbakwuru|first=Johnbosco|date=9 March 2020|accessdate=11 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March, [[Turkish Airlines]] cancelled all their flights to Nigeria due to the virus outbreak.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pulse.ng/news/local/coronavirus-turkish-airlines-cancels-flights-to-nigeria-to-curtail-disease-spread/0dx3d3n|title=Turkish Airlines cancels all flights to Nigeria to curtail Coronavirus spread|last=Famuyiwa|first=Damilare|date=10 March 2020|publisher=Pulse NG|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, a woman in Enugu State displayed the symptoms of coronavirus, she tested negative the following day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecable.ng/enugu-patient-tests-negative-for-coronavirus|title=Enugu patient tests negative for coronavirusdate=16 March 2020|date = 15 March 2020|publisher=[[TheCable]]|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March 2020, Nigeria postponed the 20th national sports festival that was supposed to hold in [[Benin City]], Edo State from 22 March to 1 April.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/news/headlines/382312-just-in-nigeria-postpones-national-sports-festival-over-coronavirus.html|title=Nigeria postpones National Sports Festival over coronavirus|publisher=[[Premium Times]]|last=Eludini|first=Tunde|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, the management of the [[National Youth Service Corps]] suspended the 2020 Batch A stream one 21 days orientation exercise indefinitely. The orientation exercise commenced on 10 March and was expected to end on 30 March, before it was suspended after just 8 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecable.ng/breaking-nysc-shuts-orientation-camps-over-coronavirus-fears|title=NYSC shuts orientation camps over coronavirus|last=Awojulugbe|first=Oluseyi|date=18 March 2020|publisher=[[TheCable]]|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> Later the same day, Nigeria placed a travel ban on 13 countries with high cases of the virus, the countries are; [[United States]], [[United Kingdom]], [[South Korea]], [[Switzerland]], [[Germany]], [[France]], [[Italy]], [[China]], [[Spain]], [[Netherlands]], [[Norway]], [[Japan]] and [[Iran]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-fg-places-travel-ban-on-china-italy-us-uk-others|title=UPDATED: FG places travel ban on China, Italy, US, UK, nine others|last=Ogundele|first=Kamarudeen|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> In [[Katsina State]], a Nigerian citizen that returned from [[Malaysia]] displayed the symptoms of the virus, he tested negative the following day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/just-in-katsina-records-first-suspected-case-of-coronavirus|title=JUST IN: Katsina records first suspected case of coronavirus|last=Danjuma|first=Shehu|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/covid-19-suspected-case-in-katsina-tests-negative|title=COVID-19: Suspected case in Katsina tests negative|last=Danjuma|first=Shehu|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]|date=19 March 2020|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> [[Kano State]] government confirmed that three persons tested negative for the virus in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/covid-19-suspected-cases-tested-negative-in-kano-commissioner|title=COVID-19: Three suspected cases tested negative in Kano \u2014 Commissioner|last1=Bello|first1=Bashir|last2=Murtala|first2=Abdulmumin|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref> Lagos State government banned religious gatherings of over 50 worshippers for 30 days, Ogun State also banned any gathering of more than 50 people for 30 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-lagos-bans-religious-gathering-with-over-50-worshippers|title=UPDATED: Lagos bans religious gathering of over 50 worshippers|last=Ojerinde|first=Dayo|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/coronavirus-ogun-bans-clubs-restaurants-others|title=Coronavirus: Ogun bans night clubs, gatherings over 50|last=Olatunji|first=Daud|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> The [[New Afrika Shrine]] suspended all their programmes indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/afrika-shrine-suspends-activities-over-coronavirus-fears|title=Afrika Shrine suspends activities over Coronavirus fears|last=Akinkuotu|first=Eniola|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> [[Kwara State]] and Lagos State announced the indefinite closure of their public and private schools, while [[Zamfara State]], [[Sokoto State]], Katsina State, [[Niger State]], Kano State, [[Jigawa State]], [[Kebbi State]] and Kaduna State also closed down their schools for 30 days from 23 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/coronavirus-kwara-shuts-down-schools-indefinitely-from-monday|title=Coronavirus: Kwara shuts down schools indefinitely from Monday|last=Akinyemi|first=Demola|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-coronavirus-lagos-announces-closure-of-schools|title=[BREAKING] Coronavirus: Lagos announces closure of schools|last=Ojerinde|first=Dayo|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://guardian.ng/news/coronavirus-northwest-governors-to-shutdown-schools-for-30-days|last=Alabi|first=Abdulganiyu|title=Coronavirus: NorthWest governors to shutdown schools for 30 days|date=18 March 2020|publisher=[[The Guardian (Nigeria)|The Guardian Newspaper]]|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Nigeria Football Federation]] suspended all football activities for four weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-nff-shuts-down-football-activities-for-28-days|title=NFF shuts down football activities for 28 days|last=Oyeleke|first=Sodiq|date=18 March 2020|accessdate=18 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, Anambra State government announced the closure of their schools and suspension of public gatherings indefinitely, tertiary institutions to close from 20 March, while primary and secondary schools to close from 27 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/anambra-orders-closure-of-schools-over-coronavirus|title=Anambra orders closure of schools over Coronavirus|last=Okafor|first=Tony|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> Ogun State government extended an earlier ban to schools and religious centres in the state indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/coronavirus-ogun-shuts-schools-indefinitely|title=Coronavirus: Ogun shuts schools indefinitely|last=Olatunji|first=Daud|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> Federal government announced the closure of tertiary institutions, secondary and primary schools.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-coronavirus-fg-orders-closure-of-varsities-schools-nationwide|title=[UPDATED] Coronavirus: FG orders closure of varsities, schools nationwide|last=Olaleye|first=Aluko|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> Enugu State government also ordered the closure of all primary and secondary schools in the state from 27 March.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/coronavirus/382740-coronavirus-enugu-govt-shuts-down-primary-secondary-schools.html|title=Coronavirus: Enugu Govt. shuts down primary, secondary schools|publisher=[[Premium Times]]|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, Nigeria extended their travel ban to two more countries, [[Sweden]] and [[Austria]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pmnewsnigeria.com/2020/03/20/nigeria-adds-austria-sweden-to-travel-ban|title=Nigeria adds Austria, Sweden to travel ban|date=20 March 2020|website=[[P.M. News]]|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref> Ekiti State government banned social, political, religious and family gatherings of more than 20 persons. The state also ordered the closure of all their schools from 23 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-coronavirus-work-from-home-fayemi-tells-ekiti-civil-servants|title=Coronavirus: Work from home, Fayemi tells Ekiti civil servants|last=Nejo|first=Abiodun|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> Nigeria announced the closure of their international airports, [[Enugu]], [[Port Harcourt]] and [[Kano]] airports from 21 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/covid-19-fg-shuts-enugu-port-harcourt-and-kano-airports|title=Covid-19: FG shuts Enugu, Port Harcourt and Kano Airports|last=Ajayi|first=Omeiza|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref> Rivers State government also announced the closure of all their schools and directed the restriction of all religious activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/coronavirus-rivers-government-closes-schools|title=Coronavirus: Rivers government closes schools|last=Nwakaudu|first=Simeon|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref> Osun State government banned any public gatherings of more than 50 persons in the state with immediate effect, including schools, churches and mosques.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/coronavirus-osun-bans-public-gatherings-shuts-schools-religious-centres|title=Coronavirus: Osun bans public gatherings, shuts schools, religious centres|last=Abubakar|first=Shina|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref> [[Delta State]] government announced the closure of all their schools from 26 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/covid-19-okowa-orders-closure-of-all-schools-in-delta|title=COVID-19: Okowa orders closure of all schools in Delta|last=Ahon|first=Festus|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, [[Nasarawa State]] government confirmed that five persons tested negative for the virus in the state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/covid-19-5-suspected-cases-in-nasarawa-tested-negative-govt|title=COVID-19: 5 suspected cases in Nasarawa tested negative \u2014 Govt.|last=Odama|first=David|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref> Kebbi State government announced the indefinite closure of all their primary and secondary schools.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/covid-19-kebbi-orders-schools-closure|title=COVID-19: Kebbi orders schools' closure|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> The [[Nigerian Railway Corporation]] also announced the suspension of all passenger services from 23 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-fg-suspends-railway-services-monday-as-coronavirus-cases-increase|title=UPDATED: FG suspends railway services Monday as coronavirus cases increase|last=Oyero|first=Kayode|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> Lagos State government reduced the number of people allowed in any religious or social gathering from 50 to 20.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/covid-19-lagos-bans-gatherings-of-over-20|title=COVID-19: Lagos bans gatherings of over 20|last=Shobiye|first=Hamed|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref> Nigeria announced the closure of the remaining two international airports, [[Abuja]] and [[Lagos]], from 23 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/breaking-fg-shuts-lagos-abuja-airports-monday-as-coronavirus-cases-hit-22|title=UPDATED: FG shuts Lagos, Abuja airports Monday as coronavirus cases hit 22|last=Oyero|first=Kayode|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> Osun State reviewed their previous ban on public gatherings of more than 50 persons and changed it to a complete ban, enforcing it on all public gatherings in the state under any banner or organisation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://punchng.com/coronavirus-osun-bans-church-services-sunday-mar-22|title=Coronavirus: Osun bans church services Sunday, Mar 22|last=Oyero|first=Kayode|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020|publisher=[[The Punch|The Punch Newspaper]]}}</ref> Oyo State government ordered the closure of schools in the state.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://dailypost.ng/2020/03/21/covid-19-makinde-orders-closure-of-schools-in-oyo-inaugurates-emergency-centres|title=Covid-19: Makinde orders closure of schools in Oyo, inaugurates emergency centres|publisher=[[Daily Post (Nigeria)|Daily Post Nigeria]]|last=Adebayo|first=Musliudeen|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> [[Bayelsa State]] government also ordered the closure of all schools in the state from 26 March and restriction of all public gatherings above 50 persons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/covid-19-bayelsa-govt-shuts-schools-restricts-gathering-in-worship-centres-clubs|title=COVID-19: Bayelsa Govt shuts schools, restricts gathering in worship centres, clubs|last=Royal|first=David|date=22 March 2020|accessdate=22 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref> [[Imo State]] government also announced the indefinite closure of all schools in their state with immediate effect.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/coronavirus-imo-orders-closure-of-schools|title=Coronavirus: Imo orders closure of schools|last=Duruiheoma|first=Damian|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=21 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, Edo State government announced the closure of all their schools from 23 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/coronavirus-edo-shuts-down-schools|title=Coronavirus: Edo shuts down schools|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=22 March 2020|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, [[Ebonyi State]] government banned all public gatherings in the state, including weddings, seminars, conferences, burials and any other large gatherings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/covid-19-ebonyi-bans-burials-weddings-for-one-month|title=Covid-19: Ebonyi bans burials, weddings for one month|last=Anioke|first=Ogochukwu|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=23 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Niger State government announced a shut down in the state, restricting movement from 8am to 8pm everyday, from 25 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/breaking-niger-declares-lockdown-over-covid-19|title=BREAKING: Niger declares lockdown over COVID-19|last=Asishana|first=Justina|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=23 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Kano State government suspended all gatherings in the state indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/kano-suspends-official-gatherings-directs-closure-of-event-centres|title=Kano suspends official gatherings, directs closure of event centres|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=23 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Rivers State government announced a partial lockdown in their state, closing cinemas, nights clubs, public parks, weddings, burials and religious worship centres from 24 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/breaking-wike-announces-partial-lockdown-of-rivers-over-covid-19|title=BREAKING: Wike announces partial lockdown of Rivers over COVID-19|last=Odiegwu|first=Mike|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=23 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Edo State announced an indefinite ban of any gathering of more than 50 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/covid-19-obaseki-urges-residents-not-to-panic-as-edo-records-first-case|title=Covid-19: Obaseki urges residents not to panic, as Edo records first case|last=Olaniyi|first=Bisi|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=23 March 2020|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> The Chief Justice of Nigeria, [[Tanko Muhammad]] ordered all courts in Nigeria to shut down from 24 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/covid-19-cjn-orders-courts-to-shut-down-from-tuesday|title=COVID-19: CJN orders courts to shut down from Tuesday|last=Nnochiri|first=Ikechukwu|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=23 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref> Nigeria ordered the closure of all land borders for four weeks and the suspension of Federal Executive Council, (FEC) meetings indefinitely.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/fg-closes-all-land-borders-suspends-fec-meetings-to-contain-covid-19|title=BREAKING: FG closes all land borders, suspends FEC meetings to contain COVID-19|last=Royal|first=David|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=23 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref> Anambra State government banned all public gatherings in the state with more than 30 persons, including weddings, festivals, funerals and clubs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2020/03/obiano-orders-civil-servants-to-work-from-home-suspends-marriages-burials|title=Obiano orders civil servants to work from home, suspends marriages, burials|last=Royal|first=David|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020|publisher=[[Vanguard (Nigeria)|Vanguard Newspaper]]}}</ref> The [[Independent National Electoral Commission]] announced suspension of all their activities for fourteen days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saharareporters.com/2020/03/23/just-inec-shuts-activities-nationwide-over-coronavirus-0|title=JUST IN: INEC Shuts Activities Nationwide Over Coronavirus|date=23 March 2020|publisher=[[Sahara Reporters]]|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> Ondo State government banned all political, religious and social gatherings in the state for fourteen days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saharareporters.com/2020/03/23/just-ondo-government-orders-workers-stay-home-closes-night-clubs-others-over-coronavirus|title=JUST IN: Ondo Government Orders Workers To Stay At Home, Closes Night Clubs, Others Over Coronavirus|date=23 March 2020|publisher=[[Sahara Reporters]]|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref> Oyo State government also banned all social gatherings in the state with more than 30 persons, including religious services, parties, burials and weddings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/makinde-bans-gathering-of-more-than-30-persons-over-covid-19|title=Makinde bans gathering of more than 30 persons over COVID-19|last=Adeniran|first=Yinka|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|The Nation Newspaper]]|date=24 March 2020|access-date=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, [[Yobe State]] government announced the closure of all their schools from 26 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/covid-19-gov-buni-shuts-down-yobe-schools-in-yobe|title=COVID 19: Gov.Buni shuts down Yobe schools in Yobe|last=Duku|first=Joel|publisher=[[The Nation (Nigeria)|T